//9.  Varargs - overloaded
//Compile-time resolution: the compiler looks at the reference type (A) and checks which methods exist.
//Run-time: overridden methods in the actual object (B) are invoked only if they override a method.
class A { void show(int... x) { System.out.println("Varargs"); } }
class B extends A { void show(int x) { System.out.println("single"); } }
A obj = new B(); obj.show(1);

//10. A
//Explanation: super.show() calls A's method.
class A { void show() { System.out.println("A"); } }
class B extends A { void show() { System.out.println("B"); } void test() { super.show(); } }
new B().test();

//11. Compilation error
//Explanation: Can't override final method, and static vs instance mismatch.
class A { final void show() {} }
class B extends A { static void show() {} }


//12. A B
//Explanation: this(5) calls other B constructor; A's constructor runs implicitly.
//If a constructor does not explicitly call super(), Java automatically inserts super() as the first statement.
class A {
   A() {
       System.out.println("A");
   }
}
class B extends A {
   B() {
       this(5);
       System.out.println("B");
   }

   B(int x) {}
}
new B();


